label.value: Accumulation Ratio AUC T1 to T2 Normalized by Dose

value.value: The area under the curve from T1 to T2 at steady state divided by the area under the curve from T1 to T2 during the initial dosing interval, each divided by the associated dose. (CDISC)

label.value: Accumulation Ratio Cmax Normalized by Dose

value.value: The maximum concentration at steady state divided by the maximum concentration during the initial dosing interval, each divided by the associated dose. (CDISC)

label.value: Accumulation Ratio Cmin Normalized by Dose

value.value: The minimum concentration at steady state divided by the minimum concentration during the initial dosing interval, each divided by the associated dose. (CDISC)

label.value: Accumulation Ratio Ctrough Normalized by Dose

value.value: The trough concentration at steady state divided by the trough concentration during the initial dosing interval, each divided by the associated dose. (CDISC)

Nucleotide sequences found upstream of exons encoding the constant regions of immunoglobulin heavy chains where exon rearrangement can occur. The combination of exons selected in a B-cell determines the immunoglobulin isotype produced by that cell.

label.value: Average Concentration from T1 to T2 Normalized by Body Mass Index

value.value: The area under the curve over the interval from T1 to T2 divided by the length of the interval and then divided by the body mass index. (CDISC)

label.value: Average Concentration from T1 to T2 Normalized by Dose

value.value: The area under the curve over the interval from T1 to T2 divided by the length of the interval and then divided by the dose. (CDISC)

label.value: Average Concentration from T1 to T2 Normalized by Surface Area

value.value: The area under the curve over the interval from T1 to T2 divided by the length of the interval and then divided by the surface area. (CDISC)

label.value: Average Concentration from T1 to T2 Normalized by Weight

value.value: The area under the curve over the interval from T1 to T2 divided by the length of the interval and then divided by the weight. (CDISC)

label.value: Day Times Microgram per Milliliter Times Kilogram per Milligram

value.value: Days times microgram per milliliter, divided by milligrams times kilograms.

label.value: Hour Times Nanomole per Liter per Milligram per Kilogram

value.value: Hours times nanomoles per liter, divided by milligrams per kilograms.

label.value: Hour Times Micromole per Liter per Milligram per Kilogram

value.value: Hours times micromoles per liter, divided by milligrams per kilograms.
An indication that the subject has fulfilled the criteria needed to continue to the next study period.
Someone from whom blood is removed for transplantation or other purpose.

An individual who is considered part of the social unit comprising one or more individuals living together (all of whom need not be related) in the same dwelling, who aggregate and share their incomes.

The portion of an antibody molecule that contains the three hypervariable regions in both the heavy and light chains. It is comprised of the amino terminal half of the light chains and at most a third of the heavy chains from the amino termini.
A female who is married to a spouse with children whom are not biologically related to her.
Any individual related biologically to an individual's father.
An individual who is believed to have likely transmitted a disease to another individual.
The volume exhaled during the first three seconds of a forced expiratory maneuver that is started from the level of total lung capacity.

label.value: PCWG Scher Prostate Cancer 2016 Oncology Response Criteria

value.value: An assessment of the bone response of a disease to a therapy.
An indication as to whether a malignancy has appeared at sites distant to the primary site of disease.
An evaluation of the soft tissue response of the disease to the therapy.
An evaluation of the tumor marker response of the disease to the therapy.
The main language that is spoken by the subject most frequently or dominantly.

Part of an immunoglobulin antibody that binds a specific antigen and consists of both a light chain and part of a heavy chain.  By comparison, natural antibodies consist of two heavy and two light chains.  An FAB (fragment antibody) offers the advantages of smaller size and lower cross-reactivity compared to the complete antibody. (NCI04)
Additional language(s) that is spoken by the subject but which is not considered the primary language.
Plasma that has been isolated from capillary blood.
Plasma that has been isolated from venous blood.
A measurement of the total number of bone tumors.
A measurement of the total number of bone tumors that have not been previously seen or characterized.

label.value: Two or More Persisting New Bone Lesions Indicator

value.value: An indication as to whether there are two or more bone tumors that have been previously seen or characterized.
The identification of a localized, pathological, or traumatic structural change, damage, deformity, or discontinuity of the bone.
A localized, pathological, or traumatic structural change, damage, deformity, or discontinuity of the bone that has not been previously seen or characterized.

The identification of a tumor or lesion that has a well-defined area of unequivocally increased signal intensity on MRI or CT scan images compared with the normal-appearing surrounding tissues, and is not the target of the therapeutic intervention.
The identification of a tumor or lesion that is present at baseline, located outside of or independent of any lymph nodes, and is not the target of the therapeutic intervention.
A protein product that results from the digestion of antibodies with papain and is comprised of the second and third constant regions of the antibody heavy chain.
The identification of a tumor or lesion located at or near the lymph node that is present at baseline, and is not the target of the therapeutic intervention.

The identification of a tumor or lesion without a well-defined area of unequivocally increased signal intensity on MRI or CT scan images compared with the normal-appearing surrounding tissues, and is not the target of the therapeutic intervention.
A unit of measurement of the number of entities per unit of area equal to 200 high powered fields.
Natural number unit of measurement for a portion of a particular type of cell (excluding red blood cell subtypes) per 2000 red blood cells.
Natural number unit of measurement for a portion of a particular type of cell (excluding white blood cell subtypes) per 2500 white blood cells.
A unit of measurement of the number of entities per unit of area equal to 40 high powered fields.
Natural number unit of measurement for a portion of a particular type of cell (excluding white blood cell subtypes) per 500 white blood cells.
The unit of measure for the number of paired nucleotides in a DNA or RNA sequence.

label.value: Log10 50 Percent Tissue Culture Infective Dose per Milliliter

value.value: A logarithmic-scale (base 10) potency unit for measuring infectious activity of a biologic product or infectious agent preparation equal to the potency at which one milliliter of infectious material contains one 50 percent tissue culture infective dose.

label.value: Log10 50 Percent Tissue Culture Infective Dose per Microliter

value.value: A logarithmic-scale (base 10) potency unit for measuring infectious activity of a biologic product or infectious agent preparation equal to the potency at which one microliter of infectious material contains one 50 percent tissue culture infective dose.

A class of tough protein filaments (including keratin filaments, neurofilaments, desmin, and vimentin) that measure 8-10 nm in thickness and comprise part of the cytoskeleton of the cytoplasm of most eukaryotic cells; so named because they are intermediate in thickness between actin filaments and microtubules.

A unit of concentration based on the vaccine specific number of titers that are the geometric mean titer at which an individual is considered to convert from a seronegative to a seropositive response due to the vaccine.
